    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix thread-unsafe access to global variables in PSS timing measurements\n\n### Summary\nThe PSS synchronization code in the NR UE stack accessed global timing variables (`generic_time` array and `opp_enabled` flag) without proper synchronization. When `sl_generate_pss()` was called from multiple threads simultaneously, this caused race conditions and unpredictable behavior in timing measurements.\n\nThis fix adds proper mutex synchronization around all accesses to these global variables when `TEST_SYNCHRO_TIMING_PSS` is enabled.\n\n### Changes\n- `openair1/PHY/NR_UE_TRANSPORT/pss_nr.c`: Added pthread mutex to protect global timing variables\n- `openair1/PHY/NR_UE_TRANSPORT/pss_nr.c`: Wrapped all accesses to `generic_time` and `opp_enabled` with mutex locks\n- `openair1/PHY/NR_UE_TRANSPORT/pss_nr.c`: Added pthread.h include for mutex support\n\n### Reproduction\nWhen running the NR UE stack with multiple threads calling `sl_generate_pss()` concurrently and `TEST_SYNCHRO_TIMING_PSS` enabled, the application would exhibit inconsistent timing measurements and occasional crashes due to race conditions on the global timing variables. The issue was more pronounced under high CPU load conditions.\n"
}